The '''letter-winged kite''' ('''''Elanus scriptus''''') is a small, rare and [[Irruptive growth|irruptive]] bird of prey that is [[endemism|found only]] in Australia. Measuring around {{convert|35|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length with a wingspan of {{convert|84|-|100|cm|in|abbr=on}}, the adult letter-winged kite has predominantly pale grey and white plumage and prominent black rings around its red eyes. Its name derives from its highly distinctive black underwing pattern of a shallow 'M' or 'W' shape, visible when in flight. This distinguishes it from the otherwise similar [[black-shouldered kite]]. This species is also the only nocturnal species within the order [[Accipitriformes]] despite few differences found in its visual anatomy to other closely related kites.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Keirnan |first1=Aubrey |last2=Worthy |first2=Trevor H. |last3=Smaers |first3=Jereon B. |last4=Mardon |first4=Karine |last5=Iwaniuk |first5=Andrew N. |last6=Weisbecker |first6=Vera |title=Not like night and day: the nocturnal letter-winged kite does not differ from diurnal congeners in orbit or endocast morphology |journal=Royal Society Open Science |date=2022 |volume=9 |issue=5 |page=17 |doi=10.1098/rsos.220135 |pmid=35620001 |pmc=9128852 |bibcode=2022RSOS....920135K |s2cid=249019479 |doi-access=free }}</ref>

The species begins breeding in response to [[rodent]] outbreaks, with pairs nesting in loose colonies of up to 50&nbsp;birds each. Three to four eggs are laid and incubated for around thirty days, though the eggs may be abandoned if the food source disappears. Chicks are [[fledge]]d within five weeks of hatching. Roosting in well-foliaged trees during the day, the letter-winged kite hunts mostly at night. It is a specialist predator of rodents, which it hunts by hovering above grasslands and fields. It is rated as [[Near-threatened species|near threatened]] on the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN)'s [[IUCN Red List|Red List]] of Threatened Species.

==Taxonomy==
The letter-winged kite was [[Species description|described]] by ornithologist [[John Gould]] in 1842 under its current [[Binomial nomenclature|binomial name]] ''Elanus scriptus''.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Gould | first=John | author-link=John Gould | year=1842 | title=''Elanus scriptus'' | journal=Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London | volume=Part 10 | page=80 | url= https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/30679842 }}</ref> The specific epithet is from the [[Latin]] word ''scriptum'', meaning "written" or "marked".<ref>{{cite book|last = Simpson | first= D.P.| title = Cassell's Latin Dictionary | publisher = Cassell Ltd.| year = 1979|edition = 5th|location = London|page=539| isbn=0-304-52257-0}}</ref> British explorer [[Charles Sturt]] wrote of seeing them on his travels in his 1849 book ''Narrative of an Expedition into Central Australia''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Sturt|first1=Charles|title=Narrative of an Expedition into Central Australia, Performed Under the Authority of Her Majesty's Government, During the Years 1844, 5, and 6: Together with a Notice of the Province of South Australia, in 1847, Volume 2|date=1849|publisher=T. and W. Boone|location=London|page=16|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EvEfJuZGSRQC&pg=RA1-PA13}}</ref> The letter-winged kite is monotypic: no subspecies are recognised,<ref name="ioclist"/> nor is there any recorded geographic variation.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=52}} Molecular evidence shows that the letter-winged kite and its relatives belong to the subfamily [[Elaninae]], an early offshoot within the [[Bird of prey|raptor]] family [[Accipitridae]].<ref name="lerner2005"/><ref name="griffiths2007"/> There is some evidence that they may be more divergent from other raptors and better placed in their own family.<ref name="Wink"/><ref name="Ausraptors"/>

"Letter-winged kite" has been designated as the official English-language name by the [[International Ornithologists' Union]] (IOU),<ref name="ioclist">{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | year=2019 | title= New World vultures, Secretarybird, kites, hawks & eagles | work=World Bird List Version 9.2 | url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/raptors/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref> derived from the letter-like markings under the wings.<ref name="fraser13">{{cite book |last1=Gray |first1=Jeannie |last2=Fraser |first2=Ian |title=Australian Bird Names: A Complete Guide |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W1TCqHVWQp0C&pg=PT73 |year=2013 |publisher=Csiro Publishing |location=Collingwood, Victoria |isbn=978-0-643-10471-6 |page=73}}</ref> In [[Central Australia]], southwest of [[Alice Springs]], the [[Pitjantjatjara dialect|Pitjantjatjara]] name for the letter-winged kite is ''nyanyitji<u>r</u>a''.<ref>{{cite book |first=Cliff | last= Goddard|title= Pitjantjatjara/Yankunytjatjara To English Dictionary |year=1992 |edition=2nd|publisher=Institute for Aboriginal Development |location=Alice Springs |isbn= 0-949659-64-9 |page=95}}</ref> It has been incorrectly called white-breasted [[sparrowhawk]].{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=45}}

==Description==
[[File:Letter-winged Kite (Elanus scriptus)3.jpg|left|thumb|A letter-winged kite in flight, Birdsville Track, South Australia. The underwing markings are visible. |alt=the underside of a Letter-winged kite]]
The adult letter-winged kite is about {{Convert|35|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length, with a wingspan between {{convert|84|and|100|cm|in|abbr=on}}. The female is slightly heavier, averaging {{convert|310|g|oz|abbr=on}} compared to the male's average weight of {{convert|260|g|oz|abbr=on}}. The sexes have similar plumage. The adult male has pale grey upperparts, wings and nape with a white head and white underparts. It has large deep-red eyes, which are surrounded by a black eye patch. Its bill is black, with a dark grey-brown [[Beak#Cere|cere]] at its base. Its wings are marked with a black shoulder patch above and a striking black line underneath, which runs from the primary [[Covert feather|coverts]] to the body,{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=45}} and which resembles a letter 'M' or 'W' when flying.<ref name="backyardbirds">{{Cite web | title = Letter-winged Kite | work = Birds in Backyards | publisher = Birds Australia, Australian Museum | date = 11 November 2009 | url = http://birdsinbackyards.net/species/Elanus-scriptus | access-date = 10 May 2010 }}</ref> The central [[Flight feather#Rectrices|rectrices]] of the tail are pale grey, while the rest of the tail feathers are white. The legs and feet are a fleshy pinkish white or white.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=45}} The feet have three toes facing forwards and one toe facing backwards.<ref name="Slater70">{{cite book |title=A Field Guide to Australian Birds: Non-passerines |last=Slater |first=Peter|year=1970 |publisher=Rigby |location=Adelaide |isbn=0-85179-102-6|page=239}}</ref> The female is similar but can be distinguished by a greyer crown,<ref name="backyardbirds"/> and its grey plumage is slightly darker all over.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=51}} [[Moulting]] has been recorded from all months except May and August, and is probably related to breeding.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=52}}

The juvenile has a white lower forehead, face, chin and throat, with a brownish orange band across the forehead, neck and breast. It has a similar dark eye patch to the adult, and the eyes themselves are dark brown. The hindneck is grey-brown, and the upperpart feathers are grey-brown with orange tips. The rump and central tail rectrices are pale grey tipped with orange. The bill is black with a brownish grey cere.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=45}}

The letter-winged kite soars with v-shaped upcurved wings, the primaries slightly spread and the tail fanned, giving it a square appearance. When flying actively, it beats its wings more slowly and deeply than the [[black-shouldered kite]] (''Elanus axillaris''). The wing beats are interspersed with long glides on angled wings. It can also hover motionless facing into the wind and flapping its wings.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=45}} The 'M' or 'W' on the underside of its wing and lack of black wing tips help distinguish it from the black-shouldered kite. Additionally, the latter species is diurnal, not nocturnal.<ref name="backyardbirds"/> At night, the letter-winged kite could be mistaken for the [[eastern barn owl]] (''Tyto javanica'') or [[eastern grass owl]] (''T. longimembris''), but these species have large heads; longer and trailing legs; blunted wings; and stockier bodies. The [[grey falcon]] (''Falco hypoleucos'') has somewhat similar colouration to the letter-winged kite but is bulkier and heavier overall, and lacks the black markings.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=46}}

===Vocalisations===
The letter-winged kite is generally silent when alone but often noisy when breeding or roosting communally at night, beginning to call at the rising of the moon.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=49}} Its calls have been described as chicken-like chirping or a repeated loud {{not a typo|kacking}},<ref name="Slater70"/> and at times resemble those of the barn owl or black-shouldered kite. A rasping call, or ''scrape'', composed of six or seven half-second long notes is the main [[contact call]] between a pair. It is often used by the female in answer to a whistle by her mate, when a bird alights at the nest, or—loudly—in response to an intruder. The male can utter a loud whistle in flight, which can serve as an alarm call. Mated pairs chatter to one another at night in the colony.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=49}}<!-- cites previous 3.5 sentences -->

==Distribution and habitat==
The usual habitat of the letter-winged kite is arid and [[Semi-arid climate|semi-arid]] open, [[Shrubland|shrubby]] or [[Grassland|grassy]] country, across the arid interior of the continent, particularly the southern [[Northern Territory]], particularly the [[Barkly Tableland]], and northeastern [[South Australia]], and [[Queensland]], where it is relatively common in western areas south of [[20th parallel south|20° south]], and has been recorded as far afield as [[Townsville]] and [[Stradbroke Island]]. In South Australia it may reach the [[Eyre Peninsula]] and southeastern corner on occasion. The species is generally rare in [[New South Wales]]:{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=46}}<!-- cites previous 4 sentences --> it has been recorded in the vicinity of [[Broken Hill]] in the far west,<ref>{{cite web |title=Broken Hill Complex – biodiversity |url=https://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/bioregions/BrokenHillComplex-Biodiversity.htm |website=Office of Environment and Heritage | date = 26 April 2016 |publisher=State of New South Wales and Office of Environment and Heritage |access-date=8 October 2018}}</ref> and twice in [[Inverell]] in the north of the state—once found dead in a street in 1965 and once spotted alive a year later.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Baldwin|first=Merle|year=1975|title=Birds of Inverell District|journal=Emu|volume=75|issue=2|pages=113–120|doi=10.1071/MU9750113 |bibcode=1975EmuAO..75..113B }}</ref> It is rare in [[Western Australia]].{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=46}}

Its abundance or even presence in any given area is heavily dependent on availability of food; spells of significant rainfall inland lead to surges in rodent numbers, which in turn lead to [[Irruptive growth|irruptions]] of letter-winged kites.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=46}}<!-- cites previous 2 sentences --> Nesting and raising multiple broods in succession, the kite population may increase ten-fold.<ref name="Garnett11"/> Major irruptions have taken place in 1951–53, 1969–70, 1976–77,{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=46}} and 1993–95.<ref name="RaptorsWorld">{{Cite book |last1=Ferguson-Lees |first1=James |first2=David A. |last2=Christie |others=illustrated by Kim Franklin, David Mead, and Philip Burton |title=Raptors of the World |publisher=Christopher Helm |year=2001 |location=London |pages=360–362 |isbn=978-0-7136-8026-3}}</ref> Eventually dry conditions lead to a fall in rodent numbers and dispersal of birds, which often starve if they fail to find prey elsewhere.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=46}}

==Behaviour==
[[File:Letterwinged Kite Sunny Roost Diamantina 2019.jpg|thumb|Roosting in Diamantina basin, Queensland|alt=several Letter-winged kites on horizontal branches]]
The letter-winged kite typically hunts at night, with daytime foraging taking place in areas of superabundant or scarce prey.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=46}} By day, birds roost in leafy trees with plenty of cover, in colonies of up to 400 individuals, becoming active at dusk.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=46}} Their social behaviour is poorly known on account of their nocturnal habits and shy nature, being difficult to approach when roosting.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=49}}

===Breeding===
Within its range, the letter-winged kite generally breeds in an area covering the [[Diamantina River|Diamantina]] and [[Lake Eyre basin|Lake Eyre]] drainage basins, [[Sturt Stony Desert]], eastern [[Simpson Desert]] and Barkly Tableland, to [[Richmond, Queensland]], and [[Banka Banka Station]] in the north and Boolkarie Creek, South Australia, in the south. Nesting has also been recorded in [[Exmouth Gulf]] and southwest Western Australia, the southwest of the Northern Territory, and the [[Clarence River (New South Wales)|Clarence River]] district and northwest of New South Wales.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=46}}<!-- cites two previous sentences --> The birds nest in colonies of up to 50 pairs, and have more than one nest and brood at once. At times their nests are close to those of [[spotted harrier]]s (''Circus assimilis''), [[black kite]]s (''Milvus migrans''), [[whistling kite]]s (''Haliastur sphenurus''), [[brown falcon]]s (''Falco berigora'') and [[black falcon]]s (''Falco subniger'').{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=49}}<!-- cites previous 2 sentences -->

[[File:Letter-winged Kite (Elanus scriptus)6.jpg|thumb|right|On a nest in foliage in Birdsville Track, South Australia|alt=A Letter-winged kite in a nest in a tree obscured by foliage]]
It is not known if breeding pairs remain bonded after breeding.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=48}} Aerial courtship displays involve mutual flight high above the nest, with the male flying much higher than the female and holding its wings high with rapidly fluttering wingtips. He drops near its mate, who responds by holding her wings in a similar manner. The two then chatter while circling each other. Copulation often follows.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=48}}

There does not appear to be a set breeding season; instead, the species forms nesting colonies in response to rodent irruptions. Birds produce broods for as long as the rodents are abundant, and stop when their food source declines.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=49}}<!-- cites previous 2 sentences --> Often smaller trees are chosen as nesting sites over larger ones, with some preference given to the beefwood (''[[Grevillea striata]]''). Other species used include waddy (''[[Acacia peuce]]''), coolibah (''[[Eucalyptus microtheca]]'') and sheoaks (''[[Casuarina]]'' spp.). Generally there is one nest per tree,{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=50}}<!-- cites previous 3 sentences --> though there may be more than one nest in single trees when rodent irruptions provide an abundance of food. The nest is a large, untidy and shallow cup of sticks, usually located in the foliage near the top of trees, some five&nbsp;metres (15&nbsp;ft) or higher off the ground.<ref name="Beru03"/> On average it is about {{Convert|50|cm|in|abbr=on|sigfig=1}} wide and {{Convert|34|cm|in|abbr=on}} high, with a {{Convert|20|cm|in|abbr=on|sigfig=1}} diameter cup-shaped depression within.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=50}} It is lined with green leaves and other material such as regurgitated [[Pellet (ornithology)|pellets]].<ref name="Beru03"/>

The [[Clutch (eggs)|clutch]] consists of three to four, or rarely five or even six, dull white eggs measuring on average {{Convert|44 x 32|mm|in|abbr=on|sigfig=2}} with red-brown blotches and tapered oval in shape. The markings are often heavier around the larger end of the egg.<ref name="Beru03">{{cite book | last = Beruldsen | first = Gordon | title = Australian Birds: Their Nests and Eggs| publisher = self |year = 2003| location = Kenmore Hills, Queensland| page = 199|isbn=0-646-42798-9}}</ref> The female incubates the eggs for 30&nbsp;days,<ref name="backyardbirds"/> though this has been difficult to confirm due to unpredictable breeding. The young are born semi-[[Altriciality|altricial]], covered in white down with black beaks and feet and dark brown eyes. By a week old, they have pale tan down on their back and brown eyes. They are fully feathered by 3–4 weeks of age and can fly at 7&nbsp;weeks. During this time they are brooded by the female, while the male brings food at night.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=51}} He calls on his approach, at which the female flies out to receive the food and then convey it to the young. Though not known to feed the young himself, the male may at times bring food to the female on the nest. As the brood grows, the female joins the male in catching food; she may eventually begin a second brood and leave the male to feed the older brood.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=49}} Nestlings [[fledge]] at around 32&nbsp;days,<ref name="backyardbirds"/> although have been known to be abandoned if the food supply suddenly disappears.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=51}} Birds in juvenile plumage reach sexual maturity within their first year of age.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=51}}

===Food and hunting===
The letter-winged kite hunts mainly in the first two hours after sunset. It flies at a height of {{Convert|10|to|20|m|ft|abbr=on|round=5}}, moving in wide circles scanning the ground, then hovers at a height of up to {{Convert|30|m|ft|abbr=on|sigfig=1}}. When prey is spotted, the kite drops silently onto it, feet-first with wings raised high.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=48}}

The letter-winged kite's principal prey is the [[long-haired rat]] (''Rattus villosissimus''). When population numbers of this [[rodent]] build up, following significant rainfall, the kites are able to breed continuously and colonially so that their numbers increase in parallel.<ref name="backyardbirds"/> One Central Australian study over two and a half years found that, within six months of an outbreak starting, the birds had relocated to that location.<ref name="Paveymamm">{{cite journal|last1=Pavey |first1=Chris R.| last2= Eldridge | first2=Stephen R. | last3= Heywood | first3=Mike |year=2008|title=Population dynamics and prey selection of native and introduced predators during a rodent outbreak in arid Australia |journal=Journal of Mammalogy |volume=89|issue=3|pages=674–683|doi=10.1644/07-MAMM-A-168R.1|doi-access=free }}</ref> When the rodent populations decline, the now superabundant kites may disperse and appear in coastal areas far from their normal range; though they may occasionally breed in these new locations, they do not persist and eventually disappear.<ref name="backyardbirds"/>

Across Central Australia, the letter-winged kite shares its habitat with other nocturnal rodent hunters, the eastern barn owl and eastern grass owl; the former species prefers larger rodents such as the [[plains rat]] (''Pseudomys australis''), whereas the kite hunts all species, including the [[sandy inland mouse]] (''Pseudomys hermannsburgensis'') and [[spinifex hopping mouse]] (''Notomys alexis''), on availability.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pavey |first1=Chris R.| last2= Gorman | first2=J.| last3= Heywood | first3=Mike |year=2008|title=Dietary overlap between the nocturnal letter-winged kite ''Elanus scriptus'' and barn owl ''Tyto alba'' during a rodent outbreak in arid Australia|journal=Journal of Arid Environments|volume=72|issue=12|pages=2282–2286|doi=10.1016/j.jaridenv.2008.07.013|bibcode=2008JArEn..72.2282P}}</ref> Other predators sharing its habitat and prey include the [[dingo]], feral cat and fox. Overall, letter-winged kites average one rodent consumed per day.<ref name="Paveymamm"/> They have also been recorded hunting the introduced [[house mouse]] (''Mus musculus'') in north-eastern South Australia.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Baker-Gabb | first1=David J.| last2= Pettigrew | first2=J. D.|author-link=David Baker-Gabb|year=1982|title=Non-breeding diet of the Letter-winged Kite in north-eastern South Australia|journal=Corella|volume=6|pages=19–20}}</ref> Other animals recorded as prey include rabbit, [[fat-tailed dunnart]] (''Sminthopsis crassicaudata''), [[stripe-faced dunnart]] (''Sminthopsis macroura''), [[Forrest's mouse]] (''Leggadina forresti''&thinsp;), beetles and spur‐throated locust (''Nomadacris guttulosa'').{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=48}}

===Predation===
Black falcons have been reported hunting adult letter-winged kites, while black kites have taken nestlings.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=51}}

==Conservation status==
The letter-winged kite's fluctuations in abundance make its conservation status difficult to assess,<ref name="iucn status 12 November 2021" /> though it is clearly much less common than the black-shouldered kite.<ref name="RaptorsWorld"/> It also rarely comes into contact with people across most of its range.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=46}} It is rated as [[near threatened]] on the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN) [[IUCN Red List|Red List]] of Threatened Species,<ref name="iucn status 12 November 2021" /> as its population may number as low as 1,000 individuals between irruptions.<ref name="Garnett11"/> It is unknown to what extent competition for food with the [[Red foxes in Australia|introduced red fox]] or [[Feral cats in Australia|feral cat]],<ref name="Paveymamm"/> or if habitat degraded by [[Overgrazing#Australia|overgrazing]], have an impact on the letter-winged kite. It is not known whether the population has increased or decreased overall since European settlement.<ref name="RaptorsWorld"/> <!-- cites previous 3 sentences -->

